3":"1393","about 1350":"about 1350","1405":"1405","Beverston, Cotswold district, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Beverston, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Wogan","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Welsh, English, and Irish (Dublin): from the Old Welsh personal name <i>Guoccaun</i>, which derives from the ancestor of Modern Welsh <i>gogawn</i> ‘honour, glory’. In Middle Welsh it became <i>Gwogon</i> and <i>Gwogan</i> and was adopted as a surname by a south Pembrokeshire Anglo-Norman family in the normanized or Anglicized pronunciation <i>Wogan</i>. Compare   Cadogan  . In Ireland the name has been Gaelicized as <b>Úgán</b>.","History: A family of this name settled in County Kildare following the Anglo-Norman invasion of the 12th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Ogan","meanings":["Irish: of Welsh origin, a variant of   Wogan  , found Gaelicized as <b>Úgán</b>."]},{"name":"Vogan","meanings":["Irish: of Welsh origin, a variant of   Wogan  ."]},{"name":"Cadogan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Dermot.","Welsh (Pembrokeshire and Glamorgan) and Irish (of Welsh origin): from the Old Welsh personal name <i>Catgucaun</i>, <i>Catguocawn</i>, modernized as <i>Cadwgon</i>. It is composed of <i>cad</i> ‘battle’ + <i>gogawn</i> ‘honour, glory’. See also   Wogan  . The surname is stressed, like its Welsh original, on the penultimate syllable, hence its occasional development to   Duggan  .","Irish: from <b>Ó Ceadagáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Ceadagán</i>’."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Agnes Wogan was born about 1350, in England, United Kingdom. She had at least 2 sons with John Elyot. She died in 1405, in her hometown, at the age of 56."},"et":{"about 1350–1405":"umbes 1350–1405","1350–1410":"1350–1410","1369–1393":"1369–1393","1376–1430":"1376–1430","1350–1405":"1350–1405","1369":"1369","1410":"1410","1376":"1376","1430":"1430","1350":"1350","1393":"1393","about 1350":"umbes 1350","1405":"1405","Beverston, Cotswold district, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Beverston, Gloucestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"fi":{"about 1350–1405":"noin 1350–1405","1350–1410":"1350–1410","1369–1393":"1369–1393","1376–1430":"1376–1430","1350–1405":"1350–1405","1369":"1369","1410":"1410","1376":"1376","1430":"1430","1350":"1350","1393":"1393","about 1350":"noin 1350","1405":"1405","Beverston, Cotswold district, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Beverston, Gloucestershire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"fr":{"about 1350–1405":"environ 1350–1405","1350–1410":"1350–1410","1369–1393":"1369–1393","1376–1430":"1376–1430","1350–1405":"1350–1405","1369":"1369","1410":"1410","1376":"1376","1430":"1430","1350":"1350","1393":"1393","about 1350":"environ 1350","1405":"1405","Beverston, Cotswold district, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"B